This dataset of learning results (as measured by exam points) and possibly explanatory variables consists of 166 observations and 7 variables. Here is a graphical overview of the dataset:

ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(col = gender, alpha = 0.2), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 25)))

There is somewhat high correlation between attitude and points, but otherwise the variables are pretty uncorrelated. All variables have mostly similar distributions for both genders. Genders are marked with coloring.

first_model <- lm(learning2014$points ~ learning2014$attitude + learning2014$stra + learning2014$surf)

There is very high statistical significance for attitude as explainer of exam points.

plot(second_model, which = 1)

Constant variance of errors assumption holds well.

plot(second_model, which = 2)

The QQ plot implies that the errors have reasonably normal distribution, though there are some problems in both extremes.

plot(second_model, which = 5)

No observation has abnormally large leverage, making the model seem more reasonable.

We will study relationships of high/low alcohol consumption and other variables. For the sake of this exercise, other variables are âactivitiesâ (has extracurricular activities), âfreetimeâ (amount of free time after school), âgooutâ (amount of going out with friends) and âhealthâ (current health status). Working hypothesis would be that an increase in any of the first three or a decrease in the last one implies assumed higher alcohol consumption. The relationships might not be that strong though.

We will first take a look at activities:

table(high_use = alc$high_use, activities = alc$activities)
##         activities
## high_use  no yes
##    FALSE 122 146
##    TRUE   59  55
plot(ggplot(alc, aes(x = activities)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = high_use)))

Here it seems there is pretty much no relation between high alcohol consumption and extracurricular activies, so the working hypothesis is false; in fact, the small difference in this set of observations actually goes to the opposite direction.

Next we will look at free time:

table(high_use = alc$high_use, freetime = alc$freetime)
##         freetime
## high_use   1   2   3   4   5
##    FALSE  15  49 113  70  21
##    TRUE    2  16  40  41  15
plot(ggplot(alc, aes(x = freetime)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = high_use)))

Preliminarily the working hypothesis seems much better here: there are not many students who consume lots of alcohol while not having much free time after school, but considerable portion of the students with the most free time consume lots of alcohol.

Variable that measures going out with friends might behave somewhat similarly, so we will take a look at it:

table(high_use = alc$high_use, goout = alc$goout)
##         goout
## high_use   1   2   3   4   5
##    FALSE  19  84 103  41  21
##    TRUE    3  16  23  40  32
plot(ggplot(alc, aes(x = goout)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = high_use)))

Indeed, the first observations are very similar to free time variable and the relationship seems to be even stronger here.

Lastly, we will take a look at health:

table(high_use = alc$high_use, health = alc$health)
##         health
## high_use  1  2  3  4  5
##    FALSE 35 28 62 49 94
##    TRUE  11 16 19 18 50
plot(ggplot(alc, aes(x = health)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = high_use)))

Here we see that the biggest portion of students with high alcohol consumption actually lies in the top fifth of health status. So it might be that at the age of these students, good health enables high alcohol consumption, while the negative effects of that consumption to health are still negligible.

Overall, the relationship between health and high alcohol consumption seems to be weak here.

We will now fit a logistic regression model with these variables:

m <- glm(high_use ~ activities + freetime + goout + health, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)

Only the variable âgooutâ has statistically significant relationship with high/low alcohol consumption in this model. We should look at the odds ratios and their confidence intervals:

OR <- coef(m) %>% exp()
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp()
cbind(OR, CI)
##                       OR       2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept)   0.01921623 0.005488501 0.06222816
## activitiesyes 0.69538475 0.430469070 1.11809527
## freetime      1.12587388 0.866572754 1.46498319
## goout         2.10684951 1.670305678 2.69462900
## health        1.13304588 0.954811883 1.35049332

Indeed, confidence intervals for odds ratios of all other variables contain 1, the break-even point so it makes sense that their predictive power would be low. Concerning the working hypothesis, the hypothesis holds for âgooutâ, but other relationships are perhaps even weaker than anticipated, at least in this particular model.

We will now fit a new model with the only significant variable, âgooutâ:

m_goout <- glm(high_use ~ goout, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m_goout)
## 
## Call:

We will use this model to make predictions:

probabilities <- predict(m_goout, type = "response")
predictions <- (probabilities > 0.5)
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = predictions)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   247   21
##    TRUE     82   32

103 predictions out of 382 were wrong, so the predictive power is not especially high even if it is better than a simple coin flip.

Lastly, we will try cross validation:

# loss_func from DataCamp exercises
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m_goout, K = 10)

cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2696335

The model has about the same performance as the one in DataCamp exercises, but using just one variable for predictions.

After standardization, all variables have mean 0 and variance 1.

For linear discriminant analysis, we will assign 80% of the data to a train set and the rest to a test set:

idx_sample <- sample(nrow(boston_scaled), .8*nrow(boston_scaled))
train <- boston_scaled[idx_sample, ]
test <- boston_scaled[-idx_sample, ]

Next we fit the linear discriminant analysis for the categorical crime rate variable:

lda.fit <- lda(crim ~ ., data = train)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = as.numeric(train$crim))

Using the LDA we will try to predict crime rates for the test set:

crime_observed <- test$crim
train %<>% dplyr::select(-crim)
crime_predicted <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(crime_observed, crime_predicted$class)
##               
## crime_observed  l ml mh  h
##             l  22  3  0  0
##             ml 10 11  5  0
##             mh  0  5 14  0
##             h   0  0  0 32

The predictions are good and only very rarely more than one category away from observed.

Finally we will try clustering with the k-means method:

# no need to reload Boston dataset since we have not edited it at all
boston_kmeans <- as.data.frame(scale(Boston))
boston_dist <- dist(boston_kmeans)
km <- kmeans(boston_dist, centers = 10)
pairs(boston_kmeans, col = km$cluster)

10 clusters is probably too much, so we will want to see how good results are with less clusters:

twcss <- sapply(1:20, function(.) {kmeans(boston_dist, .)$tot.withinss})
qplot(1:20, twcss)

2 clusters already gives good results, but there seems to be value in going for 3 or maybe even 4 clusters. We will run the algorithm again for 4 clusters and visualize:

km4 <- kmeans(boston_dist, centers = 4)
pairs(boston_kmeans, col = km4$cluster)

We can also look at LDA for these clusters:

# arrows function from DataCamp exercises
# based originally on this one here:
# http://stackoverflow.com/questions/17232251/how-can-i-plot-a-biplot-for-lda-in-r
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

boston_kmeans$cluster <- km4$cluster
lda.cluster <- lda(cluster ~ ., data = boston_kmeans)
plot(lda.cluster, dimen = 2, col = km4$cluster)
lda.arrows(lda.cluster, myscale = 1.5)

Even in 2 dimensions the LDA seems to divide the clusters pretty neatly, though there is some overlap. Variables âindusâ (proportion of non-retail business acres per town) and âznâ (proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.) are the most influential separators; and notably both are measures of land allocation.
